<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-01-03T09:32:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-01-03T09:32:00-05:00" n="297" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d297">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">824.51/230: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cottrell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">La
                                        Paz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-03T10:00:00-04:32"><hi rend="italic">January 3,
                                        1924—10 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 2
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1. Your number 27, December 28, 6 p.m. Congress has passed law as to
                            Potosi-Sucre Railroad and the President has signed it. I had previously
                            protested as requested.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cottrell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>